isationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/629EFB89-586B-479C-91C0-199939F4BD4A"><gtr:id>629EFB89-586B-479C-91C0-199939F4BD4A</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Andreas</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Liefooghe</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI00193X%2F1"><gtr:id>DB0AB674-D379-4943-B6BB-6D58BBF3A88F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Vulnerable selves, organizing others: New approaches to understanding bullying and conflict</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I00193X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The Human Rights and Equality Commission recently conceptualized bullying as discrimination and a breach of human rights. As they emphasise the human right to live without threats or mistreatment, our response as scholars has been prolific yet uni-dimensional, each based in their own echelon and discipline without the necessary cross fertilisation of ideas, far less theory.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This series seeks to promote interdisciplinary reflection by drawing on a much broader pool of expertise beyond the confines of organizational studies.&amp;nbsp;The central reason for slow empirical and practical progress is the absence of good theory which:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>can help account for the variety of ways employees are vulnerable at work in relation to others&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>can provide the basis of effective interventions.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The aims are to:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>bring together users and academics from a variety of different disciplines, perspectives and backgrounds&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>undertake a fundamental review of current theory, methods and practices in the fields of bullying and conflict&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>enhance theory, research and practice that meet the simultaneous criteria of relevance and rigour&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>explore alternative paradigms, methodologies and practical interventions&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>enhance dialogue amongst research and practitioner communities.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

